GUI
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.awt.event.ActionListener, java.awt.image.ImageObserver, java.awt.MenuContainer, java.io.Serializable, java.util.EventListener, javax.accessibility.Accessible, javax.swing.RootPaneContainer, javax.swing.WindowConstants
public class GUI
extends javax.swing.JFrame
implements java.awt.event.ActionListener
This class handles all programming logic for constructing and framing the Word Occurrences GUI as well as retrieving the website data and parsing it for entries.

This relies heavily on the free JSoup library to efficiently handle parsing HTML documents.

  • Method Details

    • create

      public void create()
      Upon construction, this method is called. It sets default closing behavior, window naming, layout, element sizes, and adds in elements.

      Critically, this method also adds in an actionListener for the button to ensure the program works. Elements are then packed in and setup for their inactive state for the listener to change.

      The important elements whose properties are changed later are stored as private fields to ensure they can be accessed within the class outside of this method.

    • actionPerformed

      public void actionPerformed​(java.awt.event.ActionEvent e)
      This method overrides the actionPerformed abstract method to set behavior for execution.

      In this case, the listener will change the button text to indicate execution has begun, and then call the analyzer() method to retrieve sorted results. It will then construct an output list of text and append it into the JTextArea from the create() method for viewing.

      This method requires a try/catch block due to the need to handle the exceptions thrown by analyzer().

      Specified by:
      actionPerformed in interface java.awt.event.ActionListener

    • analyzer

      public static java.util.SortedSet<java.util.Map.Entry<java.lang.String,​java.lang.Integer>> analyzer() throws java.lang.Exception
      This method constructs a TreeMap object that handles sorting and equivalence for words in a poem. It first establishes a connection to the site hosting the poem, then retrieves the HTML to get text. It then parses it for the words of the poem and uses a BiFunction to match words to frequency.

      The method will then call the entriesSortedByValues() method to sort the values and then return the new list for display.

      This method uses the JSoup library to handle parsing of an HTML document retrieved from a website.

      Returns:
      Returns a SortedSet object that contains every unique word in the poem matched to its frequency.
      Throws:
      java.lang.Exception - Handles the possible IOException or connection failure that may occur when attempting to retrieve data from a website.

    • entriesSortedByValues

      static <K,​ V extends java.lang.Comparable<? super V>> java.util.SortedSet<java.util.Map.Entry<K,​V>> entriesSortedByValues​(java.util.Map<K,​V> map)
      This method allows for the sorting of TreeMaps by their values rather than their keys, something that normally must be done by manually pulling out every value from the map and then sorting. This method is critical for the GUI class because the words that are found must be the keys to the map. Keys cannot be repeated, but values can. As such, words will only appear once if set as a value.

      By using the comparator within this method and changing the object type to SortedSet, the map now can be read in order of frequencies rather than by alphabetical order for the key word values.

      Type Parameters:
      K - A generic variable for TreeMap objects that handles unknown data types for the key.
      V - A generic variable for TreeMap objects that handles unknown data types for the value.
      Parameters:
      map - A generic map object that is passed for sorting by its values.
      Returns:
      Returns a sorted TreeMap object as a SortedSet object, where the SortedSet is now sorted by values rather than keys.
